\begin_layout Title
Status competitions under extreme income differences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
While status-driven consumption and the appeal for social mobility through
 consumption appear to have become more prominent in recent decades, relative
 income differences have remained as permanent as differences in long-term
 wealth.
 We explain how the social promise offered by status consumption may be
 constrained by finite economic growth in an economy - which we view as
 comprising of disparate income bands that the consumers transition through
 while gaining social mobility.
 Viewing status consumption as intertemporal choice to invest towards the
 probabilistic social mobility in long-term, we explore the implications
 of contentment with one's one income bands due to social or cultural barriers
 for social mobility in the economy.
\end_layout

