\begin_layout Standard
The above set up for status competitions implies a short-term Nash equilibrium
 as consumers optimise total accumulated assets subject to their band-reference
 in a given period.
 The simplest instance of this short-term optimisation is one where the
 consumers in an economy comprising of a poor band 1 and a rich band 2 optimise
 the assets accumulated in a single period.
 In other words, the representative consumer in the two-bands economy has
 just one life and a one shot-investment to make towards her life-time status.
 We also consider that the consumer receives a higher utility from the same
 value of assets when she is in a poorer band compared to when she is in
 a richer band.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the consumers optimise savings at the end of the first-time horizon,
 we do not expect them to spend on status consumption at the end of their
 lives.
 This very idea that the consumers optimise value at a finite-time horizon
